related.headline: MVP returns from foot injury, family matters

article.headline: Bird's 23 lead Seattle rout
article.linkText: Jackson returns, helps Storm snap 3-game skid
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson is back, Sue Bird is scoring and
everything seems right again with the Seattle Storm.

Jackson returned from a three-game absence and scored 15 points,
helping Seattle snap a three-game losing streak with an 86-67
victory over the Detroit Shock on Wednesday night.

Jackson, the league MVP who had been on the injured list with a
right foot sprain, was activated before the game. While sidelined,
Jackson traveled to her native Australia to visit her ill
grandmother.

"It's been really emotional for me," Jackson said. "You've
got to live, got to move on. It was good to get out there and just
play with my teammates."

The victory was Seattle's first since returning from the Olympic
break, and the win kept the Storm in second place in the Western
Conference.

Bird carried the scoring load in Jackson's absence and didn't
let up against the Shock, scoring 23 points on 8-for-9 shooting,
including 19 in the second half. She was 3-for-3 on 3-pointers and
finished with eight assists.

"Some nights I'm going to be passing the ball off, and some
nights I'm going to be shooting," Bird said. "In the second half,
I got some open looks."

The Storm appeared to be headed toward their fourth straight
loss when Detroit made eight of its first 13 shots and charged to
an 18-5 lead.

Seattle surged back, scoring 14 straight points to take a 19-18
lead. The Storm kept the run going, outscoring Detroit 41-14 over
the final 14 minutes of the first half for a 46-32 lead at the
break.

Seattle scored the first six points of the second half and
Detroit never got closer than 16.

"I don't think I've seen this team, in two years, have that
kind of sense of urgency," Seattle head coach Anne Donovan said.
"I can't say enough for that effort in the first half to not only
climb back out of the hole, but to take control."

Betty Lennox added 15 points and the Storm received seven or
more points from seven players.

Cheryl Ford led Detroit with 16 points and 10 rebounds, while
Swin Cash added 15 and Deanna Nolan finished with 14. The Shock
struggled from the floor and shot only 39 percent against a Seattle
team that allowed opponents to shoot 50 percent in Jackson's
absence.

"We had control of the game early and I made a mistake and went
to a zone defense," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "They then
made a couple of shots that shook our confidence and we weren't
able to recover."

With the win, Seattle (18-11) tied a franchise record for
victories in a season.
